  "texts": [
    "In addition, the specific content of items can contribute to differential item functioning (DIF), which occurs when individuals from different groups (e.g., based on gender or race) with the same underlying ability level have different probabilities of answering an item correctly, due to the characteristics of the item itself rather than the test-takers' ability.",
    "For example, an LLM might generate an item that includes a cultural reference or terminology familiar to one group of students but not to another.",
    "Suppose a generated reading comprehension item references a traditional Western holiday like Thanksgiving Day.",
    "Students from cultural backgrounds where Thanksgiving is not celebrated may find the item more challenging, not because they have lower reading comprehension ability, but because they are unfamiliar with the cultural context.To address this ethical issue, several techniques can be implemented during multiple stages of training LLMs, including pre-processing, in-training, and post-processing (Gallegos et al., 2024).",
    "For instance, an effective method is the inclusion of diverse datasets in the preprocessing phase, enabling the model to learn from a wider array of contexts and reducing the likelihood of generating biased content (Buolamwini & Gebru, 2018)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}